{
  "query": "What's a strong B2B SaaS cold email sequence? Sequence length (3-7 emails), spacing (3-7 days), pattern (relevance hook → value → social proof → CTA → bump → break-up). Subject line craft (4 U's, specificity, no clickbait). Personalization at scale. Failure modes: 'just checking in', generic openings, multi-question CTAs, no relevance signal, immediate hard sell?",
  "text": "## The sequence that actually works\n\nMost cold email sequences fail before the first reply because they're built around what the sender wants to say, not what the recipient needs to hear. The 40/40/20 principle cuts through this: **60-80% of your outcome is determined by list quality and offer relevance before a single word is written.** Get those wrong, and no subject line trick saves you.\n\nHere's the structure worth building.\n\n---\n\n## Sequence architecture: 5 emails, not 7\n\nSeven emails is overkill. After five touches with no response, you've learned something: either the targeting is wrong, the offer doesn't resonate, or the timing is bad. A break-up email wraps it, then you move on or change the angle.\n\n**Email 1 (Day 1): Relevance hook + single value claim**\nOpen with something specific to *them*: a recent funding round, a job posting that signals a pain, a product launch, a LinkedIn post they wrote. One sentence. Then connect it to a specific outcome you deliver. One CTA: a calendar link, nothing else.\n\n**Email 2 (Day 4): The problem reframe**\nDon't restate your pitch. Come at the pain from a different angle. \"Most [job title]s I talk to are dealing with X. Usually it's because of Y.\" This signals pattern recognition, not desperation.\n\n**Email 3 (Day 8): Social proof, specific**\nA named customer (if you can), a result with a number, and the context that makes it relevant to them. \"A [similar company type] cut [metric] by [X] in [timeframe].\" Specificity does the work here. Vague testimonials are invisible.\n\n**Email 4 (Day 13): Different angle or asset**\nOffer something: a relevant piece of research, a short Loom walking through their website, a framework doc. Value before ask. This is where behavior-based personalization matters: if they clicked Email 1, they're warmer than someone who never opened. Adjust accordingly.\n\n**Email 5 (Day 18): The break-up**\n\"I've reached out a few times and haven't heard back. I'll assume the timing isn't right. If that changes, [one-line reminder of what you do].\" Short. No guilt. Sometimes this gets the highest reply rate of the sequence because it signals you're not going to keep pestering them.\n\n---\n\n## Subject line craft\n\nThe four U's framework (urgent, unique, useful, ultra-specific) is the right lens, but **ultra-specific does the most lifting in cold outreach.** Generic subject lines like \"Quick question\" or \"Following up\" used to work. Buyers are immune now.\n\nWhat works instead:\n- Reference something real: \"[Company] + [your category]\" or \"Saw your post on [topic]\"\n- Signal the value, not the ask: \"How [Competitor] cut [metric] by 30%\" beats \"Intro to [Your Company]\"\n- Keep it under 8 words, no title case, no exclamation points\n\nThe test: would this subject line make sense sent from a colleague? If yes, send it. If it reads like marketing, rewrite it.\n\n---\n\n## Personalization at scale\n\nThe trap is spending 45 minutes researching one prospect when you need to reach 500. The pattern that scales: **one custom line per email, everything else templated.**\n\nThat custom line should reference something findable in under 90 seconds: their LinkedIn headline, a recent company announcement, a job posting that signals the pain you solve. Tools like Clay can pull this context automatically and merge it into your first sentence.\n\nBehavior-based sequencing matters too. Someone who clicked your link twice is not the same as someone who never opened. Most teams treat them identically. That's a missed signal.\n\n---\n\n## The failure modes worth naming\n\n- **\"Just checking in\"**: signals you have nothing new to say. Every follow-up needs a new angle or a new asset.\n- **Generic openings**: \"I hope this finds you well\" or \"My name is X and I work at Y\" are the fastest way to the trash folder.\n- **Multi-question CTAs**: \"Would you be open to a call? Or if not, happy to send more info. Or maybe a quick 15 minutes?\" Pick one. One CTA, one action, one decision.\n- **No relevance signal**: if the email could have been sent to anyone in the industry, it reads like spam. Even one specific detail changes the psychology.\n- **Immediate hard sell**: the first email asking for a 45-minute demo is asking for too much trust too fast. Micro-commitments first: a reply, a click, a calendar link.\n\n---\n\nThe sequence is the container. What fills it is specific insight about why *this person*, *this company*, *this moment* makes the outreach worth their 30 seconds.\n\nWhich of these failure modes is most alive in your current sequences?",
